gw.api.util

Class Range<T>

  • java.lang.Object
    • gw.api.util.Range<T>

  • public class Range<T>
extends java.lang.Object
    Represents a value range, which can be open or closed at either end, or indefinite at either end. Examples:
    • All numbers between zero and one (exclusive) - [0, 1)
    • All strings between "S" and "T" (exclusive) - ["S", "T")
    • All positive numbers - (0, ∞)

    Intervals are typically over Comparable objects, but they can also be over non-Comparable objects, if a Comparator is supplied to the range.

    Author:
    pdalbora

      • isEmpty

        public boolean isEmpty()
        Determines whether the given range is empty, i.e., whether includes(T) will return false for every input.

        Note that it's possible to have ranges for which includes(T) will always return false, but which return true for this method. This can happen when dealing with open ranges. For example, the integer range (0, 1) is not empty, but includes(T) will always return false, because no integer exists between 0 and 1.
